Additional project policies (EasyIR)

These terms apply in addition to the MIT license above and are intended to
clarify community expectations. If any provision below conflicts with mandatory
applicable law, the law governs to the minimum extent required.

1) Attribution for reuse

   If you copy, adapt, or redistribute material from this repository (code,
   documentation, or other creative content), you must provide clear, prominent
   attribution that names:

   - the original author (Badalyan Vyacheslav), and
   - the project name ("EasyIR").

   Attribution should be placed where a reasonable recipient will see it
   (for example: LICENSE or NOTICE file, package metadata, or documentation
   credits).

2) Forking under a new project name

   You may fork this repository under the terms of the MIT license. Publishing
   a fork under a **new name** (a name other than "EasyIR" or a good-faith
   variant clearly derived from it, such as a personal fork prefix) is allowed
   **only if** the upstream EasyIR repository (this project’s default branch on
   the canonical upstream you forked from) had **no new commits** for at least
   **365 consecutive days** immediately before you first publish the renamed
   fork.

   If the upstream repository remains actively maintained, forks that intend to
   compete as a separately branded project must coordinate with maintainers or
   keep naming aligned with normal open-source fork conventions (for example,
   retaining upstream identity in documentation and credits).
